06165nam a22008775i 9783110796285DE-B159720221107062033.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221107t20222022gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2022940051  a97831107962857 a10.1515/97831107962852doi  a(DE-B1597)626172  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aREL1140002bisacsh00aHellenism, Early Judaism, and Early Christianity :bTransmission and Transformation of Ideas /ced. by Radka Fialová, Jiří Hoblík, Petr Kitzler. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (VII, 243 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aArbeiten zur Kirchengeschichte ,x1861-5996 ;v15500tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tI Hellenism, Judaism, and Christianity: Theological and Philosophical Trajectories -- tGod’s Power and Powers in Philo of Alexandria -- tThe Presence of the Myth in the Pentateuch: A Platonic Argument in Philo of Alexandria -- tGreek Heritage Reinterpreted by Jews and Christians -- tResurrection in the Intertext: Pagan Sources in Paul’s Areopagus Speech (Acts 17:22–31) -- tThe Notion of Divine Infinity and Unknowability: Philo, Clement, and Origen of Alexandria in a Polemic with Greek Philosophy -- tOrigen’s Philosophical Theology, Allegoresis, and Connections to Platonism -- tAn Arithmological Metaphor for the Holy Trinity in Gregory of Nazianzus (Or. 29.2; 23.8) and Its Neopythagorean Background -- tII Hellenism and Judaism: Trajectories in Literature and (Material) Culture -- tRewriting the Genesis Sequence. The Account of the Titanomachy in the Third Book of the Sibylline Oracles Reconsidered -- tFamous Forgiveness: The Reception of the Prayer of Manasseh in Byzantium (with a Transcription of Hesychios of Jerusalem’s Scholia from MS Oxford, Auct. D.4.1) -- tThe Elephant Mosaic Panel in the Huqoq Synagogue: A Reappraisal of the Maccabean Interpretation -- t‘Seal of Solomon’ on a Bilingual defixio from Carnuntum (Pannonia) -- tOn the Authors -- tIndex Locorum -- tIndex of Names and Subjects0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPapers collected in this volume try to illuminate various aspects of philosophical theology dealt with by different Jewish and early Christian authors and texts (e.g. the Acts of the Apostles, Philo, Origen, Gregory of Nazianzus), rooted in and influenced by the Hellenistic religious, cultural, and philosophical context, and they also focus on the literary and cultural traditions of Hellenized Judaism and its reception (e.g. Sibylline Oracles, Prayer of Manasseh), including material culture ("Elephant Mosaic Panel" from Huqoq synagogue). By studying the Hellenistic influences on early Christianity, both in response to and in reaction against early Hellenized Judaism, the volume intends not only to better understand Christianity, as a religious and historical phenomenon with a profound impact on the development of European civilization, but also to better comprehend Hellenism and its consequences which have often been relegated to the realm of political history.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 4aHellenismus. 4aPentateuch. 4afrühes Christentum. 4afrühes Judentum. 7aRELIGION / Ancient.2bisacsh  aEarly Christian and Jewish Literature.  aHellenism.  aHistory of Thought.  aPhilosophical Theology.1 aCielontko, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrostini, Barbara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDelgado, Ana Carolina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFialová, Radka, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFranek, Juraj, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary